  "AWS/Cloud Core Services": {
    youtubeLink: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r4YIdn2eTm4",
    notes: "### ☁️ AWS / Cloud Core Services\n\n#### 🖥️ Compute:\n- **EC2**: Virtual machines. Full control, but you manage OS and patches.\n- **Lambda**: Serverless functions. Pay per execution, auto-scaling.\n- **ECS/EKS**: Container orchestration (Docker/Kubernetes managed).\n\n#### 💾 Storage:\n- **S3**: Object storage. Unlimited capacity, 11 9's durability.\n  - Standard → Infrequent Access → Glacier (cost tiers).\n- **EBS**: Block storage for EC2 (like a virtual hard drive).\n\n#### 🌐 Networking:\n```\nVPC (Virtual Private Cloud)\n├── Public Subnet  (Internet Gateway → ALB → EC2)\n├── Private Subnet (App Servers, Databases)\n└── NAT Gateway    (Private → Internet, outbound only)\n```\n\n#### 🔐 IAM (Identity & Access Management):\n- **Users**: Individual accounts.\n- **Roles**: Temporary permissions for services.\n- **Policies**: JSON documents defining permissions.\n- **Principle of Least Privilege**: Grant minimum necessary access."
  },
  "Terraform & IaC": {
    youtubeLink: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7xngnjfIlK4",
    notes: "### 🏗️ Terraform – Infrastructure as Code\n\nTerraform lets you define, provision, and manage infrastructure using declarative HCL code.\n\n#### 📄 HCL Syntax:\n```hcl\nprovider \"aws\" {\n  region = \"us-east-1\"\n}\n\nresource \"aws_instance\" \"web\" {\n  ami           = \"ami-0c55b159cbfafe1f0\"\n  instance_type = \"t3.micro\"\n  \n  tags = {\n    Name        = \"web-server\"\n    Environment = \"production\"\n  }\n}\n\noutput \"public_ip\" {\n  value = aws_instance.web.public_ip\n}\n```\n\n#### 🔄 Terraform Workflow:\n```bash\nterraform init      # Download providers\nterraform plan      # Preview changes\nterraform apply     # Apply changes\nterraform destroy   # Tear down infrastructure\n```\n\n#### 💾 State Management:\n- Terraform tracks infrastructure state in `terraform.tfstate`.\n- **Remote backends** (S3 + DynamoDB) for team collaboration and state locking.\n- Never edit state manually—use `terraform import` and `terraform state mv`.\n\n#### 📦 Modules:\n```hcl\nmodule \"vpc\" {\n  source  = \"terraform-aws-modules/vpc/aws\"\n  version = \"5.0.0\"\n  cidr    = \"10.0.0.0/16\"\n}\n```\nModules are reusable infrastructure components (like functions for infra)."
  },
  "Ansible & Configuration Management": {
    youtubeLink: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1id6ERvfozo",
    notes: "### 🔧 Ansible – Agentless Configuration Management\n\nAnsible automates software provisioning, configuration, and application deployment.\n\n#### 📄 Playbook Structure:\n```yaml\n---\n- name: Configure Web Servers\n  hosts: webservers\n  become: yes  # Run as root\n  \n  tasks:\n    - name: Install Nginx\n      apt:\n        name: nginx\n        state: present\n        update_cache: yes\n    \n    - name: Copy Nginx config\n      template:\n        src: nginx.conf.j2\n        dest: /etc/nginx/nginx.conf\n      notify: Restart Nginx\n    \n    - name: Ensure Nginx is running\n      service:\n        name: nginx\n        state: started\n        enabled: yes\n  \n  handlers:\n    - name: Restart Nginx\n      service: { name: nginx, state: restarted }\n```\n\n#### 📋 Inventory:\n```ini\n[webservers]\nweb1 ansible_host=10.0.1.10\nweb2 ansible_host=10.0.1.11\n\n[databases]\ndb1 ansible_host=10.0.2.10\n```\n\n#### 🔑 Key Concepts:\n- **Idempotent**: Running the same playbook twice produces the same result.\n- **Agentless**: Uses SSH, no software to install on target machines.\n- **Roles**: Reusable collections of tasks, handlers, and templates."
  },
  "Monitoring & Observability Stack": {
    youtubeLink: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9TJx7QTrTyo",
    notes: "### 📊 Monitoring & Observability Stack\n\nYou can't fix what you can't see. Observability is the ability to understand system behavior from its outputs.\n\n#### 📈 Prometheus (Metrics):\n```yaml\n# prometheus.yml\nscrape_configs:\n  - job_name: 'myapp'\n    static_configs:\n      - targets: ['app:3000']\n```\n\n#### 🔍 PromQL (Prometheus Query Language):\n```\n# Request rate per second\nrate(http_requests_total[5m])\n\n# 95th percentile latency\nhistogram_quantile(0.95, rate(http_request_duration_seconds_bucket[5m]))\n\n# Error rate percentage\nrate(http_requests_total{status=~\"5..\"}[5m]) / rate(http_requests_total[5m]) * 100\n```\n\n#### 📊 Grafana Dashboards:\n- Connect to Prometheus as data source.\n- Create dashboards for CPU, Memory, Request Rate, Error Rate, Latency.\n- Set up **Alerting** rules (Slack, PagerDuty, Email).\n\n#### 📝 ELK/EFK Stack:\n```\nApp Logs → Fluentd/Filebeat → Elasticsearch → Kibana\n(collect)    (ship)            (index/search)  (visualize)\n```\n- Centralized logging for debugging across microservices.\n- Use structured JSON logging for efficient searching."
  },
  "SRE Principles & Practices": {
    youtubeLink: "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uTEL8Ff1Zvk",
    notes: "### 🏗️ SRE (Site Reliability Engineering) Principles\n\nSRE is what happens when you ask a software engineer to design an operations team.\n\n#### 📊 SLIs, SLOs & Error Budgets:\n- **SLI (Service Level Indicator)**: A measurement. Example: 'Request latency < 200ms'.\n- **SLO (Service Level Objective)**: A target. Example: '99.9% of requests < 200ms'.\n- **SLA (Service Level Agreement)**: A contract with consequences.\n- **Error Budget**: 100% - SLO = room for risk.\n  ```\n  99.9% SLO = 0.1% error budget\n  = ~8.7 hours of downtime per year\n  = ~43 minutes per month\n  ```\n  When error budget is exhausted → freeze deployments, focus on reliability.\n\n#### 🚨 Incident Management:\n1. **Detect**: Automated alerts (Prometheus, PagerDuty).\n2. **Respond**: On-call engineer acknowledges alert.\n3. **Mitigate**: Quick fix (rollback, restart, scale up).\n4. **Resolve**: Root cause fix and deploy.\n5. **Postmortem**: Blameless analysis, action items.\n\n#### 🐒 Chaos Engineering:\n- **Chaos Monkey** (Netflix): Randomly kills production instances.\n- **Litmus Chaos**: Kubernetes-native chaos experiments.\n- Purpose: Discover weaknesses before they cause real outages.\n- Start small: Inject latency → Kill pods → Network partition."
  }
